#Key Learning
A single exposed file path in source code can reveal a username that unlocks an entire digital identity across platforms. PGP keys stored publicly in repositories are not anonymous — they carry the owner's email address and can be decrypted with freely available tools. Cryptocurrency wallets are permanently public and traceable — every transaction, mining pool, and wallet interaction is visible to anyone with the address. AI tools can extract meaningful geolocation intelligence from images even without EXIF metadata, identifying airports, landmarks, and bodies of water from visual content alone. Chaining small pieces of individually harmless data across platforms builds a complete and detailed profile of a person's identity, finances, and physical location.

#What I Would Flag in a Real SOC
Source code and file paths left in publicly accessible pages can expose system usernames and directory structures — code review before publication is essential and often overlooked.
PGP keys published in public repositories expose the owner's email address — this is a common OSINT entry point that developers frequently underestimate.
Cryptocurrency wallet addresses should never be considered anonymous — all transactions are publicly auditable on-chain. Using a wallet address in a public repository script is equivalent to publishing a financial statement.
The full geolocation chain used here — departure airport, layover, lake, nearest city — was reconstructed entirely from images shared on social media. Employees handling sensitive work should be briefed that AI can now geolocate images without EXIF data, metadata scrubbing alone is no longer sufficient protection.
Social media handles linked across platforms create a cross-platform identity graph that is trivial to map. Threat actors and investigators alike use the same technique — one username leads to email, email leads to crypto, crypto leads to location.
In a real investigation this chain would constitute a full threat actor profile built entirely from publicly available information with no privileged access required.
